Step 1: Set Up an Amazon ECR Repository Log in to the AWS Management Console and navigate to the Amazon ECR service. Create a new repository by clicking on “Create repository.” Provide a name and optional description for the repository. Note down the ECR repository Name and AWS region for later use.

[![image](https://private-user-images.githubusercontent.com/77018407/289367442-dedd6d16-460a-4090-ba50-b2b4974367f2.png?jwt=eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9..AJOG4TTP-LHujzjH_wBCAzMpFqEcCnyuDSzQh1AzkLs align="left")](https://private-user-images.githubusercontent.com/77018407/289367442-dedd6d16-460a-4090-ba50-b2b4974367f2.png?jwt=eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9..AJOG4TTP-LHujzjH_wBCAzMpFqEcCnyuDSzQh1AzkLs)

Step 2: Configure AWS Credentials Create an AWS Identity and Access Management (IAM) user with the necessary permissions to access the ECR repository. (Your IAM user must have “AmazonEC2ContainerRegistryFullAccess” IAM permissions) Obtain the AWS access key ID and secret access key for the IAM user.

Step 3: Create the Dockerfile and Push to github repository We will create a application on local machine (EC2 Ubuntu machine) and then push to github repository.

1. Create Dockerfile in vim editor
    
    [![image](https://private-user-images.githubusercontent.com/77018407/289367670-3458ac26-a3ff-42c1-9f23-78d409ce5375.png?jwt=eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9..OjWR7Rktf-EA7svDgCNJC3bbsV6X960ge7FHhBmGVSs align="left")](https://private-user-images.githubusercontent.com/77018407/289367670-3458ac26-a3ff-42c1-9f23-78d409ce5375.png?jwt=eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9..OjWR7Rktf-EA7svDgCNJC3bbsV6X960ge7FHhBmGVSs)
    
2. Workflow of Docker
    
3. ```dockerfile
            Build command          Run command
    ```
    
4. Dockerfile -------------&gt; Images ----------------&gt; Containers
    
5. docker build -t java-app:latest .
    
6. docker run -d java-app:latest
    
7. Now to push to dockerhub from local machine EC2 Ubuntu
    
8. docker login -------&gt; dockerhub credentials
    
9. docker tag java-app:latest dockerhubreponame/java-app:latest
    
10. docker push dockerhubreponame/java-app:latest
    
11. Pushing Docker image to GitHub Container Registry Step 4: Create a Personal Access Token (PAT) on GitHub: Go to your GitHub account settings. Click on Developer settings in the left sidebar, click on Personal access tokens and then Generate new token. Give your token a descriptive name, and select the following scopes: read:packages, write:packages, and delete:packages. You might also need to select the repo scope if your image is private. Click Generate token and copy the generated token. Store it securely, as you won't be able to see it again. docker login [ghcr.io](https://private-user-images.githubusercontent.com/77018407/289367442-dedd6d16-460a-4090-ba50-b2b4974367f2.png?jwt=eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9..AJOG4TTP-LHujzjH_wBCAzMpFqEcCnyuDSzQh1AzkLs) -u YOUR\_GITHUB\_USERNAME -p YOUR\_PERSONAL\_ACCESS\_TOKEN docker build -t [ghcr.io/githubuser/java-app:latest](https://private-user-images.githubusercontent.com/77018407/289367442-dedd6d16-460a-4090-ba50-b2b4974367f2.png?jwt=eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9..AJOG4TTP-LHujzjH_wBCAzMpFqEcCnyuDSzQh1AzkLs) . docker push [ghcr.io/githubuser/java-app:latest](https://private-user-images.githubusercontent.com/77018407/289367442-dedd6d16-460a-4090-ba50-b2b4974367f2.png?jwt=eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9..AJOG4TTP-LHujzjH_wBCAzMpFqEcCnyuDSzQh1AzkLs)
    

Step 5: Configure GitHub Secrets In your GitHub repository, go to “Settings” and navigate to the “Secrets” tab -&gt; ‘Actions’. Add three new secrets: AWS\_ACCESS\_KEY\_ID ,AWS\_SECRET\_ACCESS\_KEY and REPO\_NAME.

[![image](https://private-user-images.githubusercontent.com/77018407/289368196-8fb4af13-a5af-400d-87ae-6322a58abb2e.png?jwt=eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9..OiDkqUpUZ0lqQ_ESyhRQU860K637hTDoGQwiR3kjdgw align="left")](https://private-user-images.githubusercontent.com/77018407/289368196-8fb4af13-a5af-400d-87ae-6322a58abb2e.png?jwt=eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9..OiDkqUpUZ0lqQ_ESyhRQU860K637hTDoGQwiR3kjdgw)

Step 6: Pushing Dockerfile from local machine to ECR through AWS CLI

1. sudo apt-get update
    
2. sudo apt-get install awscli
    
3. aws --version
    
4. aws configure
    

[![image](https://private-user-images.githubusercontent.com/77018407/289369854-e4923af3-0eb3-40be-9795-5de3742664bf.png?jwt=eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9..sjdswJFGStD49UKucTKlrNEf6OXSsmoXNgdW_YoEN0I align="left")](https://private-user-images.githubusercontent.com/77018407/289369854-e4923af3-0eb3-40be-9795-5de3742664bf.png?jwt=eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9..sjdswJFGStD49UKucTKlrNEf6OXSsmoXNgdW_YoEN0I)

How to Create a Repo in ECR :

1. aws ecr create-repository --repository-name &lt;repo\_name&gt; --region &lt;region\_name&gt;
    
2. aws ecr get-login-password --region &lt;region\_name&gt;
    
3. aws ecr --region | docker login -u AWS -p &lt;encrypted\_token&gt; &lt;repo\_uri&gt;
    
4. docker tag &lt;source\_image\_tag&gt; &lt;target\_ecr\_repo\_uri&gt;
    
5. docker push &lt;ecr-repo-url&gt;
